postcontent:
Up for sale is a lightly used Remington Model 700 SPS chambered in .308 Winchester.  This rifle comes with a Redfield 6-18 x44 (two years old), base and scope rings, standard SPS stock with camo paint job, Knox Industries BlackHawk tactical free floating aluminum pillar bedded stock, bi pod, and hard case.    This rifle was used for hunting and only has about 500 rounds down the tube.  It has recently been cleaned for copper fouling.

Bolt action

Specific to this weapon:
 This rifle loves the 165 gr – 168 gr bullet range, and it has no problem stabilizing bullets up to the 200 gr range(that’s the heaviest I’ve personally shot out of this .308).  Prior to my hand loads, I exclusively shot Hornady 165gr SST Superformance ammo.  The Hornady SST bullets have taken multiple elk, deer, and varmints over the last few years.
 
This rifle has been cleaned and well maintained over the years.  Attached are photos of the rifle and a recent test on some ammo.  On a regular basis, this weapon shoots a ragged hole at 100 yards and is highly effective out to 600 yards. 
 
About the .308 and the Remington Model 700:
If you’re new to the .30 cal range of bullets, the .308 is an awesome rifle to start with.  If you’re new to the Remington Model 700, again, this is an awesome rifle (I have two of them).  Straight out of the box, all of my Model 700s have shot 1 MOA or better.  Ammo for the .308 WIN is readily available and basically can be found in every store that sells ammo.  This caliber rifle has more than enough power to hunt anything in SC, and a vast majority of game across the USA.  If you’re a reloader, the .308 is forgiving on your pocket and allows you to shoot on a regular basis for a fraction of the cost (of factory ammo).  I shoot on a regular basis at 600 yards with the .308 Winchester (another rifle that I have) and I’ve had nothing but success with sub MOA accuracy.

postcontent:
I have a Remington Model 700 ADL in .30-06 Springfield (Serial No 6792xxx) that I bought used in 1983. The date code on the barrel indicates that the rifle was manufactured in October 1974. This rifle has been outfitted with a Burris Fullfield 4X scope, Redfield scope mount and rings, Burris lens caps, a Pachmayr recoil pad, and a military-style adjustable leather sling with quick-detach swivels. The original iron sights have been removed.
The monte carlo walnut stock has good grain and is nicely finished. The bluing is in decent condition with the usual wear areas here and there. There is no rust or pitting anywhere. This rifle is a real shooter. The action has been glas-bedded, the barrel free-floated, and the trigger adjusted to a light, crisp pull. I have developed a couple of hand loads for this rifle that will consistently group 5 shots at or near 1" at 100 yards. (I still have the targets to prove it.)
I have not hunted with this rifle in over 25 years. It has always been very well maintained. I simply have no practical use for it anymore, so it's time to let go of it. I am asking $475 for everything described above.
